ls they need to successfully incorporate optical measurements and principles into their research. Sönke Johnsen starts with the basics, describing the properties of light and the units and geometry of measurement. He then explores how light is created and propagates and how it interacts with matter, covering topics such as absorption, scattering, fluorescence, and polarization. Johnsen also provides a tutorial on how to measure light as well as an informative discussion of quantum mechanics. The Optics of Life features a host of examples drawn from nature and everyday life, and several appendixes that offer further practical guidance for researchers. This concise book uses a minimum of equations and jargon, explaining the basic physics of light in a succinct and lively manner. It is the essential primer for working biologists and for anyone seeking an accessible introduction to optics.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhotobiology. 0aPhysiological optics. 0aPolarization (Light). 0aSCIENCEvLife SciencesvBiophysics. 0aSCIENCEvPhysicsvOptics &ampxLight. 0aSciencevOptics. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  aabsorption.  aanimal vision.  abioluminescence.  acoherent scattering.  acolor.  aelastic scattering.  aelectric field.  aelectrons.  afluorescence.  ageometry.  ahuman vision.  ainelastic scattering.  aintegrated measurements.  airradiance.  alight emission.  alight measurement.  alight.  aluminescence.  alux.  amagnetic field.  amatter.  amechanoluminescence.  aoptical energy.  aoptical measurements.  aoptics.  aparticles.  aphosphorescence.  aphoton energy.  aphotons.  aphotosynthetically active radiation.  apolarization.  apolarized light.  aq